prediction.overall_explanation: No exploitable security vulnerabilities were found that enable an untrusted attacker to gain unauthorized access, steal funds, or manipulate privileged state. The Alice contract’s `set(int)` function is publicly callable, so there is no access control to bypass. The only notable issue is a correctness/compatibility bug: `IAlice.set(uint256)` does not match `Alice.set(int256)`, so `AliceCaller.callAlice()` will not call `Alice.set` and will instead hit `Alice`’s fallback (setting `val = 1`). This is an ABI mismatch that can break intended functionality, but it does not create a new security exploit because any user can already set `val` directly on `Alice`.
